    ],
    comment: '<p><code>Rotate</code> certain shapes using <code>transform</code> can be used to obtain other shapes.</p>\n<p>Applying the <code>transform</code> property on a regular square can create a diamond, for example:</p>\n<pre><code class="language-css">#diamond {\n  transform: rotate(45deg);\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p>The default rotation point is the center of the element. <code>transform-origin</code> can change that: it can take 2 (for 2D shapes) or 3 (for 3D shapes) values, as the <code>x</code> and <code>y</code> coordinates of the new rotation point.</p>\n<p>The center of a 2D shape is:</p>\n<pre><code class="language-css">transform-origin: 50% 50%;\n/* or */\ntransform-origin: center center;\n/* for known dimensions: 500px Ã— 20em*/\ntransform-origin: 250px 10em;\n</code></pre>\n<p>Other values :</p>\n<pre><code class="language-css">transform-origin: top left;\ntransform-origin: right bottom;\ntransform-origin: left center;\n</code></pre>\n<p>This is the default rotation around its center:</p>\n<p><svg version="1.2" baseProfile="tiny" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" height="auto" viewBox="0 0 612 200"> <path fill="#596294" stroke="#000" stroke-miterlimit="5" d="M0 0h612v200H0z"/> <path fill="#fff" stroke="#000" stroke-miterlimit="2" d="M150 50h100v100H150zM428.9878 29.6985l70.7107 70.7107-70.7107 70.7106-70.7107-70.7106z"/></svg></p>\n',
